\par \pard\plain \s18\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa140\ltrpar\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af5\langfe1081\dbch\af6\afs24\loch\f3\fs24\lang1033\sl276\slmult1\ql\ltrpar{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Moore's law}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 is the observation that }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transistor_count" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
the number}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 of }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transistor" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
transistors}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 in a dense }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_circuit" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
integrated circuit}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 (IC) doubles about every two years. Moore's law is an }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observation" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
observation}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 and }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
projection}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 of a historical trend. Rather than a }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_law" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
law of physics}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, it is an }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_relationship" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
empirical relationship}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 linked to }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wright%27s_Law" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
gains from experience}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 in production. }
\par \sect\sectd\sectunlocked1\pgwsxn11906\pghsxn16838\marglsxn1134\margrsxn1134\margtsxn1134\margbsxn1134\cols2\colsx288\ltrsect\sbknone\pard\plain \s18\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa140\ltrpar\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af5\langfe1081\dbch\af6\afs24\loch\f3\fs24\lang1033\sl276\slmult1\ql\ltrpar{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The observation is named after }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Moore" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
Gordon Moore}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, the co-founder of }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairchild_Semiconductor" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
Fairchild Semiconductor}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 and }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intel" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
Intel}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 (and former CEO of the latter), who in 1965 posited a }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_growth" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
doubling every year}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 in the number of components per integrated circuit,}{{\*\bkmkstart cite_ref-2}{\*\bkmkend cite_ref-2}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moore%27s_law#cite_note-2" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
[a]}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 and projected this rate of growth would continue for at least another decade. In 1975, looking forward to the next decade, he revised the forecast to doubling every two years, a }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compound_annual_growth_rate" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
compound annual growth rate}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 (CAGR) of 41%. While Moore did not use empirical evidence in forecasting that the historical trend would continue, his prediction held since 1975 and has since become known as a "law." }
\par \pard\plain \s18\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa140\ltrpar\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af5\langfe1081\dbch\af6\afs24\loch\f3\fs24\lang1033\sl276\slmult1\ql\ltrpar{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Moore's prediction has been used in the }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiconductor_industry" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
semiconductor industry}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 to guide long-term planning and to set targets for }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Research_and_development" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
research and development}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, thus functioning to some extent as a }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-fulfilling_prophecy" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
self-fulfilling prophecy}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
. Advancements in }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_electronics" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
digital electronics}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, such as the reduction in }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price_index#Quality_change" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
quality-adjusted}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microprocessor" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
microprocessor}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 prices, the increase in }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_memory" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
memory capacity}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 (}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random-access_memory" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
RAM}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 and }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flash_memory" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
flash}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
), the improvement of }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_sensor" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
sensors}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, and even the number and size of }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
pixels}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 in }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_camera" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
digital cameras}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, are strongly linked to Moore's law. These step changes in digital electronics have been a driving force of technological and social change, }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Productivity" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
productivity}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, and economic growth. }
\par \sect\sectd\sectunlocked1\pgwsxn11906\pghsxn16838\marglsxn1134\margrsxn1134\margtsxn1134\margbsxn1134\pgndec\sbknone\pard\plain \s18\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\hyphpar0\sb0\sa140\ltrpar\cf0\kerning1\dbch\af5\langfe1081\dbch\af6\afs24\loch\f3\fs24\lang1033\sl276\slmult1\ql\ltrpar{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Industry experts have not reached a consensus on exactly when Moore's law will cease to apply. Microprocessor architects report that semiconductor advancement has slowed industry-wide since around 2010, below the pace predicted by Moore's law. However, as of 2018, leading semiconductor manufacturers have developed }{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiconductor_device_fabrication" }{\fldrslt {\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\loch\f3\hich\af3\lang255\cf9\ul\ulc0\langfe255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang255
IC fabrication processes}{}}}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 in mass production which are claimed to keep pace with Moore's law. }
